larship in exciting new ways, bringing together the disciplinary expertise of Native studies scholars from around the world. The book is particularly concerned with the Native body as a site of persistent fascination, colonial oppression, and indigenous agency, along with the endurance of these legacies within Native communities. At the core of this collection lies a dual commitment to exposing numerous and diverse disempowerments of indigenous peoples, and to recognizing the many ways in which these same people retained and/or reclaimed agency. Issues of reviewing, relocating, and reclaiming bodies are examined in the chapters, which are paired to bring to light juxtapositions and connections and further the transnational development of indigenous studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAmerican literaturexIndian authors. 0aHuman beings in art. 0aHuman body -- Symbolic aspects. 0aHuman body in literature. 0aHuman bodyxSymbolic aspects. 0aHuman figure in art. 0aIndian art -- North America. 0aIndian artzNorth America. 0aIndian artists -- North America. 0aIndian artistszNorth America. 0aIndian literature -- North America -- History and criticism. 0aIndian literaturezNorth AmericaxHistory and criticism. 0aIndian philosophy -- North America. 0aIndian philosophyzNorth America. 4aAmerican Studies : Indigenous Studies. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Anthropology. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Postcolonial Studies. 4aHistory : History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aBan´ka, EwElina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarocci, Max, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFear-Segal, Jacqueline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat